      "Agriculture is the last major industry to be transformed by machine learning — not because the technology isn't ready, but because the data is scattered across satellite passes, soil sensors, weather stations, and decades of paper records in filing cabinets. When you connect these data sources, the improvement in decision quality is dramatic. A 28,000-hectare grain and sunflower holding in Poltava Oblast was losing an estimated 8–12% of annual yield to poorly timed harvests and late-detected crop disease. After implementing HarvestIQ, that figure dropped to under 3%.",
      "**NDVI and Satellite Imagery: The Foundation**\n\nNDVI — Normalised Difference Vegetation Index — is a measure of plant health derived from satellite imagery. Healthy green vegetation absorbs red light and reflects near-infrared strongly; stressed or damaged plants show the reverse. NDVI values range from −1 (water/bare soil) to +1 (dense, healthy vegetation). A value of 0.7 in June indicates healthy winter wheat; the same field showing 0.45 in the same week of the following year warrants investigation.\n\nThe European Space Agency's Sentinel-2 satellites provide 10-metre resolution imagery every 5 days — free, via the Copernicus Open Access Hub API. For 28,000 hectares, each satellite pass generates approximately 280 million pixels of multispectral data. We process NDVI and EVI (Enhanced Vegetation Index, which is less sensitive to atmospheric interference) for each field polygon, producing a time series of vegetation health indices going back to 2017.\n\nThis time series is the primary input to our yield prediction model — but it needs to be combined with ground truth (actual historical yields, which the holding had recorded by field for 6 years) to become a predictive system.",
      "**LSTM Yield Prediction: 6-Week Forecast with ±6.3% Accuracy**\n\nLong Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks are particularly suited to time-series prediction because they can learn long-range dependencies — connecting conditions in April (planting density, soil moisture) to outcomes in August (yield) across multiple growing seasons.\n\nOur model takes as input:\n- Weekly NDVI and EVI for each field (derived from Sentinel-2)\n- Daily weather: temperature (min/max), rainfall, solar radiation (from ERA5 reanalysis)\n- Soil data: texture, organic matter content, pH (from field surveys, updated every 3 years)\n- Agronomic inputs: seeding date, variety, fertiliser applications (from the holding's field records)\n- Previous-year yield (autoregressive feature)\n\nThe model outputs a yield forecast per field per crop type for 6 weeks ahead, updated weekly as new satellite passes and weather data arrive. Training used 6 years × 847 fields × 2 crop types = approximately 10,000 field-season samples. LSTM hyperparameters were tuned via Bayesian optimisation on a temporal holdout set (2024 season, unseen during training).\n\nResult: MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error) of 6.3% on the 2025 growing season holdout, compared to ±22% for the agronomists' manual estimates. For a holding with €4.2M annual revenue, a 15.7 percentage point improvement in yield forecast accuracy translates directly to better equipment planning, earlier contract commitments, and reduced food waste.",
      "**YOLOv8 Drone Analysis: Early Disease Detection**\n\nSatellite imagery detects stress at the field level — a broad NDVI decline tells you something is wrong, but not what. Drone imagery at 2–5cm ground resolution, analysed with computer vision, tells you exactly what: septoria in winter wheat, sclerotinia in sunflower, or simply uneven germination.\n\nOur disease detection model uses YOLOv8 — the current state of the art in real-time object detection — fine-tuned on a dataset of 12,000 annotated drone images covering 14 disease classes for wheat and sunflower (collected over 3 growing seasons from the holding and supplemented with public agricultural CV datasets). The model runs on drone-captured footage as a post-processing step: after each survey flight, the operator uploads footage to the analysis portal, and within 20 minutes receives a field map with disease zones, severity ratings, and a recommended intervention.\n\nThe pipeline integrates with the holding's agrochemical management system: a confirmed sclerotinia detection in a sunflower field triggers a pre-populated spray application recommendation — field ID, product, dosage, target date — which the agronomist can approve with one click.\n\nEarly detection impact: in the 2025 season, the system detected a septoria outbreak in a winter wheat field 11 days before it would have been visible during a standard manual walkthrough. The targeted fungicide application cost €18/ha. The estimated cost of treating the same field after visible infection: €45/ha plus an estimated 12% yield loss.",
      "**UK Implementation: AHDB Data and Environmental Land Management**\n\nFor UK farms, the same architecture integrates with different data sources and has additional relevance to Environmental Land Management (ELM) schemes.\n\nThe AHDB (Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board) provides UK-specific agronomic benchmarking data — regional yield averages, variety trial results, disease prevalence maps — that can be incorporated into the prediction model as reference features. UK Land Registry parcel data replaces the Ukrainian cadastre for field boundary definitions.\n\nMore significantly, the UK government's Environmental Land Management scheme pays farmers for sustainable farming outcomes, including carbon sequestration, soil health improvement, and biodiversity. ML-driven precision application — using only the fertiliser, pesticide, or water that specific zones of the field actually need — directly reduces input costs and supports ELM outcome claims. Several UK farm groups are using satellite-NDVI monitoring as part of their Sustainable Farming Incentive (SFI) evidence pack.\n\nFor the Codeworth HarvestIQ deployment, the full implementation timeline is 14–18 weeks: 4 weeks for data collection and pipeline setup, 6 weeks for model training and validation, 4 weeks for dashboard development and agronomist onboarding, plus a 4-week supervised production period. The holding saw ROI within the first full growing season.",
