      "Support teams at growing B2B SaaS companies face a classification problem before they face a resolution problem: a ticket arrives, someone has to read it, figure out what it is about, assign it to the right team, set the right priority, and find a matching previous solution. For a project management SaaS with 4,200 business customers, this classification work was consuming 35% of the support team's time. When weekly ticket volume crossed 1,200, the manual triage process became the bottleneck for SLA compliance.",
      "**Why Fine-Tuned BERT Rather Than GPT-4o Classification?**\n\nGPT-4o can classify support tickets accurately with a well-written prompt — but at 1,200 tickets per week, the per-ticket API cost accumulates significantly. More importantly, a general-purpose LLM has no knowledge of your specific product's terminology, feature names, or error codes.\n\nFine-tuning a BERT model on the company's own historical tickets gives the model this domain knowledge and costs fractions of a cent per classification at inference time — compared to $0.002–0.005 per GPT-4o call. At 1,200 tickets per week, that is a 95%+ cost reduction for the classification step. Accuracy is also higher: fine-tuned BERT on proprietary data consistently outperforms zero-shot GPT-4o for narrow classification tasks.",
      "**Training Pipeline: 18 Months of Historical Tickets**\n\nThe training dataset: 23,400 resolved tickets labelled with issue category (14 top-level categories, 67 sub-categories), priority (Critical/High/Medium/Low), and resolution path.\n\nData preparation steps:\n1. **Deduplication**: multiple submissions by the same customer collapsed to one record\n2. **PII scrubbing**: customer names and company names replaced with [CUSTOMER] and [COMPANY] tokens\n3. **Label balancing**: weighted sampling to prevent bias toward high-frequency categories (40% of tickets were Billing)\n4. **Split**: 70% training, 15% validation, 15% test holdout\n\nFine-tuning: bert-base-uncased, 3 epochs, learning rate 2e-5, batch size 32 on an A100 GPU (4-hour run). Final accuracy on the held-out test set: 94.1% across all 14 top-level categories.",
      "**Triage Automation: Classification, Priority, and Pre-Population**\n\nThe TriageAI system integrates with Zendesk via webhook: every new ticket triggers the classification pipeline within 8 seconds of submission.\n\nOutputs per ticket: issue category with confidence score; suggested priority (category + customer tier + SLA clock + urgency language detection — 'urgent', 'blocking', 'down' trigger priority upgrade); assignee recommendation (engineer with best performance history on this category in the last 30 days); top 3 similar resolved tickets surfaced in the agent interface; and a pre-populated response draft from GPT-4o-mini based on the classified issue and knowledge base match.\n\nFor tickets where classification confidence exceeds 0.92 and the issue has a known standard resolution, the system sends an automated first response — covering 31% of all inbound tickets without agent involvement.",
      "**Results: SLA Compliance and Agent Satisfaction**\n\nFor the B2B SaaS company after 7 months:\n- Average first response time: 4.2 hours to 48 minutes (down 81%)\n- SLA compliance (first response within 4 hours for High priority): 67% to 96%\n- Classification accuracy (manual audit 3 months post-deployment): 93.8%\n- Tickets resolved without human response: 31%\n- Agent time on triage/classification: 35% to 6% of working time\n- Agent satisfaction score: +28 points\n\nFor UK B2B SaaS companies, the business case aligns with two pressures: SLA penalties in enterprise contracts and the high cost of support scaling (automation extends the existing team's capacity).\n\nFor Ukrainian SaaS companies, the same approach applies with multilingual models — XLM-RoBERTa handles mixed UA/EN queues effectively. Several Ukrainian tech companies have used TriageAI to handle mixed-language ticket queues without requiring bilingual staff for triage.",
